<chapter subject="Chemistry" id="209" name="The s-Block Elements">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>s-block elements are those in which the last electron enters the ____ orbital.</text>
            <option id="A">s</option><option id="B">p</option><option id="C">d</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Includes Group 1 and Group 2.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Group 1 elements (Li, Na, K, Rb, Cs, Fr) are called ____ metals.</text>
            <option id="A">Alkali</option><option id="B">Alkaline Earth</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Form strongly basic (alkaline) hydroxides.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Group 2 elements (Be, Mg, Ca, Sr, Ba, Ra) are called ____ metals.</text>
            <option id="A">Alkaline Earth</option><option id="B">Alkali</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Oxides found in earth crust and are alkaline.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>General electronic configuration of alkali metals is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">ns1</option><option id="B">ns2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Loose one electron to achieve noble gas core.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>General electronic configuration of alkaline earth metals is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">ns2</option><option id="B">ns1</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Loose two electrons to achieve noble gas core.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which alkali metal is radioactive?</text>
            <option id="A">Francium (Fr)</option><option id="B">Cesium</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Longest lived isotope has half-life of 21 mins.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which alkaline earth metal is radioactive?</text>
            <option id="A">Radium (Ra)</option><option id="B">Barium</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>First discovered by Curies.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Atomic and ionic radii ____ down the s-block groups.</text>
            <option id="A">Increase</option><option id="B">Decrease</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Addition of new principal shells.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ionization enthalpy ____ down the s-block groups.</text>
            <option id="A">Decreases</option><option id="B">Increases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Outer electrons are farther from nucleus.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Alkali metals give characteristic ____ colors when heated in Bunsen flame.</text>
            <option id="A">Flame</option><option id="B">Odor</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to electronic excitations.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Lithium gives ____ color to the flame.</text>
            <option id="A">Crimson Red</option><option id="B">Yellow</option><option id="C">Violet</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sodium gives yellow, Potassium gives violet.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Magnesium and Beryllium ____ impart color to the flame.</text>
            <option id="A">Do not</option><option id="B">Always</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>High excitation energy due to small size.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Group 1 metals react with water to form ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hydroxides , Dihydrogen</option><option id="B">Oxides, Oxygen</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highly vigorous reaction (except Li).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Sodium is stored under ____ to prevent reaction with air/moisture.</text>
            <option id="A">Kerosene</option><option id="B">Water</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Prevents formation of oxide/hydroxide layer.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Alkali metals dissolve in liquid ammonia to give ____ colored solutions.</text>
            <option id="A">Blue</option><option id="B">Red</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Solution contains ammoniated electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Blue color of alkali metal in liquid ammonia is due to ____ electrons.</text>
            <option id="A">Ammoniated</option><option id="B">Core</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Absorb energy in visible region.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Washing soda is Sodium ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Carbonate decahydrate (Na2CO3.10H2O)</option><option id="B">Bicarbonate</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Industrial chemical for glass/soap.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Baking soda is Sodium ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hydrogen carbonate (NaHCO3)</option><option id="B">Carbonate</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used in food industry (CO2 release on heating).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Solvay process is used for manufacture of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sodium Carbonate</option><option id="B">Sodium Hydroxide</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ammonia-Soda process.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Quick lime is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">CaO</option><option id="B">Ca(OH)2</option><option id="C">CaCO3</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Obtained by heating limestone.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Slaked lime is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ca(OH)2</option><option id="B">CaO</option><option id="C">CaCO3</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formed by reaction of CaO with water.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Plaster of Paris (POP) factor: CaSO4 . ____ H2O.</text>
            <option id="A">1/2</option><option id="B">2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hemihydrate of calcium sulfate.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Cement was first introduced by Joseph Aspdin as ____ Cement.</text>
            <option id="A">Portland</option><option id="B">Gypsum</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Resembled stone from Isle of Portland.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Setting of cement is an ____ process.</text>
            <option id="A">Exothermic</option><option id="B">Endothermic</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Involves hydration of silicates and aluminates.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Biological importance: ____ ions are abundant outside cells (extracellular).</text>
            <option id="A">Na+</option><option id="B">K+</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Involved in transmission of nerve signals.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Biological importance: ____ ions are abundant inside cells (intracellular).</text>
            <option id="A">K+</option><option id="B">Na+</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Activate many enzymes.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Central metal atom in chlorophyll is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Magnesium (Mg)</option><option id="B">Calcium</option><option id="C">Iron</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Essential for photosynthesis.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Bone and teeth structure majorly contains ____ ions.</text>
            <option id="A">Calcium (Ca2+)</option><option id="B">Magnesium</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>In form of hydroxyapatite.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Anomalous behavior of Lithium is due to ____ size and ____ charge/radius ratio.</text>
            <option id="A">Small , High</option><option id="B">Large, Low</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Polarizing power is very high.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Lithium shows diagonal relationship with ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Magnesium (Mg)</option><option id="B">Aluminum</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Similar ionic radii and charge density.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Beryllium shows diagonal relationship with ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Aluminum (Al)</option><option id="B">Magnesium</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Both form similar covalent hydrides/halides.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Suspension of slaked lime in water is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Milk of Lime</option><option id="B">Lime Water</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used in white washing.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Clear solution obtained after filtering milk of lime is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Lime Water</option><option id="B">Milk of Lime</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used for CO2 test.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Formula of Dead burnt plaster is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">CaSO4 (Anhydrous)</option><option id="B">POP</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formed by heating POP above 473 K.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Lithium is the ____ reducing agent among alkali metals in water.</text>
            <option id="A">Strongest (due to high hydration energy)</option><option id="B">Weakest</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard electrode potential is most negative.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Density of Alkali metals ____ down the group (mostly).</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Exception: K is lighter than Na.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hydration enthalpy of alkali metal ions order: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Li+ > Na+ > K+ > Rb+ > Cs+</option><option id="B">Cs+ > Rb+ > K+ > Na+ > Li+</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Smaller ion attracts more water molecules.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Alkali metal ____ are used in photoelectric cells.</text>
            <option id="A">Cesium and Potassium</option><option id="B">Lithium</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Low ionization energy makes electron ejection easy.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Melting and boiling points of s-block metals are ____ compared to transition metals.</text>
            <option id="A">Low</option><option id="B">High</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Weak metallic bonding (large atoms, few valence electrons).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Group 2 metals are ____ (harder/softer) than Group 1 metals.</text>
            <option id="A">Harder</option><option id="B">Softer</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Smaller size and 2 valence electrons increase bond strength.</explanation>
        </question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Solubility of carbonates of Group 2 ____ down the group.</text>
            <option id="A">Decreases</option><option id="B">Increases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lattice energy decrease is slower than hydration energy decrease.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Solubility of sulfates of Group 2 ____ down the group.</text>
            <option id="A">Decreases</option><option id="B">Increases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>BeSO4 and MgSO4 are highly soluble.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Solubility of hydroxides of Group 2 ____ down the group.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lattice energy decreases faster than hydration energy.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Thermal stability of carbonates of Group 2 ____ down the group.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>BaCO3 is most stable. Larger cation stabilizes larger anion.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which alkali metal forms ONLY monoxide in air?</text>
            <option id="A">Lithium</option><option id="B">Sodium</option><option id="C">Potassium</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Li2O is the primary product.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Sodium forms ____ as major oxide in excess air.</text>
            <option id="A">Peroxide (Na2O2)</option><option id="B">Monoxide</option><option id="C">Superoxide</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>State depends on cation size.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Potassium, Rubidium and Cesium form ____ as major oxides.</text>
            <option id="A">Superoxides (MO2)</option><option id="B">Peroxides</option><option id="C">Monoxides</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Large cations stabilize large O2- ion.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Alkali metal superoxides are ____ and paramagnetic.</text>
            <option id="A">Yellow / Orange</option><option id="B">Colorless</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contain unpaired electron in pi* MO.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>KO2 is used as oxygen source in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Submarines / Spacecraft</option><option id="B">Engines</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reacts with Moisture and CO2 to release O2.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Lithium is the only alkali metal to react with Nitrogeon directly to form ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nitride (Li3N)</option><option id="B">Nitrite</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Diagonal relation with Magnesium.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Potassium Carbonate ____ be prepared by Solvay process.</text>
            <option id="A">Cannot (KHCO3 is too soluble to precipitate)</option><option id="B">Can</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Technical limitation of the process for K.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Castner-Kellner cell uses ____ cathode for manufacture of NaOH.</text>
            <option id="A">Mercury (Hg)</option><option id="B">Iron</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sodium amalgam is formed.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Basic character of hydroxides of s-block: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases down the group</option><option id="B">Decreases down the group</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Easier to release OH- for larger cations.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>BeO is ____ while oxides of rest of Group 2 are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Amphoteric , Basic</option><option id="B">Acidic, Basic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Characteristic anomalous property of Be.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Formula for Carnallite ore: ____.</text>
